\f1\fs24 \
 \
\pard\pardeftab720\ql\qnatural

\f0\fs36 \cf0 Bring water, sugar, espresso powder and cocoa nibs to a boil in a fairly large pot. Simmer on low for 20 minutes. Try not to stir a lot during the simmering process - it foams like crazy when stirred. Hence the need for a fairly large pot.
\f1\fs24 \
\pard\pardeftab720\ql\qnatural

\fs20 \cf0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\ql\qnatural

\f0\fs36 \cf0 This will thicken to a syrupy consistency.
\f1 \

\f0 After 20 minutes, move the pot off the burner, put on a lid and let it sit until cold, and preferably overnight.
\f1\fs24 \
\pard\pardeftab720\ql\qnatural

\fs20 \cf0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\ql\qnatural

\f0\fs36 \cf0 After letting this steep, strain the syrup to remove the cocoa nibs using a very fine strainer.  Don't toss the espresso-infused cocoa nibs, use them in cookies or on ice cream.\
\pard\pardeftab720\ql\qnatural

\f1\fs20 \cf0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\ql\qnatural

\f0\fs36 \cf0 When you've strained the syrup, mix in the vanilla and vodka, and then pour it into a clean bottle with a tight-fitting lid and let it age for 1 month.  It will taste much better once the flavors have had a chance to mingle and get to know each other. 
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs36 *You can make an alcohol-free coffee-chocolate syrup simply by leaving out the vodka. 
